505","1537":"1537","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Anglie","England":"Anglie","Arksey, Yorkshire, England":"Arksey, Yorkshire, Anglie","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1505–":"omkring 1505–Afdød","1510–1558":"1510–1558","1535–1590":"1535–1590","1537–1600":"1537–1600","1505–Male":"1505–Afdød","1571":"1571","1590":"1590","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","about 1505":"omkring 1505","1600":"1600","1620":"1620","1510":"1510","about 1537":"omkring 1537","about 1535":"omkring 1535","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","1537":"1537","Yorkshire, England":"Jórvík, England","England":"England","Arksey, Yorkshire, England":"Arksey, Jórvík, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Jórvík, England"},"nl":{"about 1505–":"circa 1505–Overleden","1510–1558":"1510–1558","1535–1590":"1535–1590","1537–1600":"1537–1600","1505–Male":"1505–Overleden","1571":"1571","1590":"1590","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","about 1505":"circa 1505","1600":"1600","1620":"1620","1510":"1510","about 1537":"circa 1537","about 1535":"circa 1535","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","1537":"1537","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Arksey, Yorkshire, England":"Arksey, Yorkshire, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1505–":"about 1505–Deceased","1510–1558":"1510–1558","1535–1590":"1535–1590","1537–1600":"1537–1600","1505–Male":"1505–Deceased","1571":"1571","1590":"1590","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","about 1505":"about 1505","1600":"1600","1620":"1620","1510":"1510","about 1537":"about 1537","about 1535":"about 1535","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","1537":"1537","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Arksey, Yorkshire, England":"Arksey, Yorkshire, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Brewster","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a brewer of beer or ale, from Middle English <i>brewestere</i>, <i>browestere</i> ‘(female) brewer’ (from Old English <i>brēowan</i> ‘to brew’). <i>Brewer</i> is the usual term in southern England, while <i>Brewster</i> is mainly midland, northern, and Scottish.","History: The <i>Mayflower</i> Pilgrim William Brewster (1567–1644) was the son of the bailiff of the manor of Scrooby, Nottinghamshire, home of one of the earliest Puritan congregations. He was a prominent leader in Plymouth Colony from the 1620s until his death."],"variants":[{"name":"Brewer","meanings":["English: occupational name for a brewer of beer or ale, from Middle English <i>brewere</i> ‘brewer’ (an agent derivative of Old English <i>brēowan</i> ‘to brew’). Compare   Brewster  .","English (of Norman origin): Anglicized form of French <b>Bruyère</b> (see   Bruyere  ), a habitational name from a place so called in Calvados, France, from Old French <i>bruiere</i> ‘heath’.","Americanized form (translation into English) of Dutch   Brouwer  , German   Brauer   or   Breuer  , etc., all occupational names meaning ‘brewer’."]},{"name":"Bruster","meanings":["English: variant of   Brewster  .","Swiss German: variant of the topographic name   Brust   2, the suffix <i>-er</i> denoting an inhabitant."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":44,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":53,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":64,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":66,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":95,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":115,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Brewster was born about 1505, in Arksey, Yorkshire, England. He had at least 2 sons with Maude Mann. He was buried in Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"about 1505–":"umbes 1505–Surnud","1510–1558":"1510–1558","1535–1590":"1535–1590","1537–1600":"1537–1600","1505–Male":"1505–Surnud","1571":"1571","1590":"1590","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","about 1505":"umbes 1505","1600":"1600","1620":"1620","1510":"1510","about 1537":"umbes 1537","about 1535":"umbes 1535","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","1537":"1537","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Arksey, Yorkshire, England":"Arksey, Yorkshire, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1505–":"noin 1505–Kuollut","1510–1558":"1510–1558","1535–1590":"1535–1590","1537–1600":"1537–1600","1505–Male":"1505–Kuollut","1571":"1571","1590":"1590","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","about 1505":"noin 1505","1600":"1600","1620":"1620","1510":"1510","about 1537":"noin 1537","about 1535":"noin 1535","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","1537":"1537","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Arksey, Yorkshire, England":"Arksey, Yorkshire, England","Donca